entry.title: [test] Suppress generation of stack traces upon fatal errors in death tests
entry.content:
A FATAL failure in a non-official build of any test or production binary

will result in the emission of a stack trace. This is a huge boon to

developers worldwide, as it often allows developers to diagnose failures

without the aid of a debugger. It is difficult to understate the utility

of this. Keep this in mind as you read on.



A common use of death tests is to assert that some codepath generates a

FATAL error; for example, by reaching a CHECK, DCHECK, NOTREACHED,

LOG(FATAL), etc. In all of these cases, the child process will emit log

messages that are consumed by the parent test processes so that the

parent may assert that the expected failure was reached. The parent

process does not emit these messages on success, because they are not

helpful for developers -- they are the "all is good" case. Including a

stack trace in such success messages is not necessary, since the trace

will not only be seen by developers, but if it were, it would only show

the developer that everything is okay.



As it happens, the generation of a symbolized stack trace is not free,

or even cheap. To reduce overhead, and improve cycle times for

developers and in infrastructure (especially for debug builds), this CL

suppresses the generation of such stack traces in death test child

processes. As a consequence, developers of death tests who find that the

child is failing for some other reason than the one asserted by the test

may need to take extra steps to diagnose those failures.



Bug: 1517343

...and update the few tests that violate this precondition.

be a descendant of the root node.

patch stays consistent with pre-existing usage of DCHECKs, because

passed into determinePasswordStateOnLoadComplete method. It’d be set to

independently without causing side effects (changing object state in

entry.title: [DBSC] Add a metric to estimate percentage of deferred requests
entry.content:
Signin.BoundSessionCredentials.DeferredRequestDelay helps estimating how

many requests were deferred due to a missing bound cookie and for how

long.



What it doesn't say is what percentage of requests were affected by

this. We could calculate this percentage based on the total number of

requests but this would be an underestimation since not all of the

requests are actually covered by a bound session.



This CL adds a new histogram which is only recorded for requests covered

by a bound session (requiring a bound cookie) and telling whether a

request was deferred or not. The number of deferred requests should

roughly match the DeferredRequestDelay histogram count.

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 19).
entry.content:
The Kiosk tests, e.g. WebKioskTest.AlreadyInstalledOffline, are broken

when the AppStorage feature is enabled. When the AppStorage feature is

enabled, OnAppTypeInitialized is called when apps are restored from the

AppStorage file. So the app platform and the app publisher might not

ready when OnAppTypeInitialized is called. This affects Kiosk, because

Kiosk launches the app once OnAppTypeInitialized is called.



Modify the Kiosk code to use the OnAppTypePublished interface, which

means both the app platform(e.g. webapplication) and the app publish are

ready, and apps are published by the app publisher, when the AppStorage

feature is enabled. If the AppStorage feature is not enabled, we still

use the OnAppTypeInitialized interface.



Modify AppRegistryCache to provide an interface to check whether the

app type has been published by the app publisher.



Modify AppServiceProxyAsh::OnPublisherNotReadyForLaunch to save the

launch request even if there is no ChromeShelfController, because not

all cases have ChromeShelfController, e.g. Kiosk.

entry.content:
We want to disable errors to `raw_ptr` due to issues

around templates. However, a feature flag

`check_raw_ptr_to_stack_allocated` is also associated with a feature

to allow `StackAllocated` types to bypass `check_raw_ptr_fields` check.

Disabling `check_raw_ptr_to_stack_allocated` can result in new errors

for `StackAllocated*` types in the codebase, so adding a new flag that

disables the `raw_ptr` error without affecting anything

else.

entry.title: Dispatch SiteInstanceGotProcess() only when both process and site are set.
entry.content:
All uses of ContentBrowserClient::SiteInstanceGotProcess() reference

the SiteInstance's site URL, but in certain cases the site URL may be

set *after* a SiteInstance's process is set. This happens when

creating a SiteInstance that's not for any specific URL, such as for a

blank tab; if the SiteInstance ends up being used for a subsequent

navigation, its site will be assigned at response time, but the

process will be created earlier. This behavior is undesirable since

the callers will not get another signal that both the site URL and

process are available, and the current logic in

SiteInstanceGotProcess() (such as adding extensions to ProcessMap)

won't work correctly with an empty site URL. This isn't an issue for

extensions today, since we'll end up throwing away the unassigned

SiteInstance and its process and create a new SiteInstance and process

at response time due to a mismatch in RenderProcessHostPrivilege, but

longer term we'd like to both remove those privilege buckets and allow

the unassigned SiteInstance and its initial process to be reused by

navigations to extensions, so this CL is a prerequisite for that.



This CL fixes the issue by dispatching SiteInstanceGotProcess() only

when the process and the site have both been assigned for a particular

SiteInstance, which is what its use cases really want. It also

renames the function to SiteInstanceGotProcessAndSite() to better

convey the semantics and removes an unused override in Cast code.
